<div id="review_1724055663" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1724055663" />
    <a title="Pete Skillman" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/7550900-pete-skillman"><img alt="Pete Skillman" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1327809734p2/7550900.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1724055663?book_show_action=true">Jul 05, 2017</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Pete Skillman" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Pete Skillman" href="/user/show/7550900-pete-skillman">Pete Skillman</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1724055663" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16411658972766549761">The book consists almost totally of primary sources with some commentary stringing them together. I found it difficult to engage with while I was reading because it is not laid out in a narrative form, rather the source material is grouped by subject matter, and not necessarily laid-out in chronological order. I imagine that this will make it an *excellent* reference volume, even if the &quot;story&quot; is hard to follow.</span>
  <span id="freeText16411658972766549761" style="display:none">The book consists almost totally of primary sources with some commentary stringing them together. I found it difficult to engage with while I was reading because it is not laid out in a narrative form, rather the source material is grouped by subject matter, and not necessarily laid-out in chronological order. I imagine that this will make it an *excellent* reference volume, even if the "story" is hard to follow.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16411658972766549761" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
